	abstract = {In this work, we study and analyze the performance of physical layer algorithms for Adaptive MIMO-OFDM wireless systems that employ a new class of adaptive antenna systems known as reconfigurable antennas. These antennas are capable of adaptively modifying their radiation characteristics and thus leverage pattern diversity to affect how the transmitter and receiver perceive the wireless channel. We propose a low complexity spatial AMC algorithm that uses the advantages of pattern reconfigurable antennas in concert with link adaptation to improve MIMO-OFDM link throughput. The algorithm operates in two main stages; First, it searches for the antenna configuration that yields the highest post-processing Signal-to-Noise Ratio (ppSNR) and, then, applies Adaptive Modulation and Coding (AMC) to improve spectral efficiency. The performance of the proposed scheme is experimentally evaluated for a 2x2 MIMO-OFDM wireless system in an indoor environment. },
